-- LESSON 1: Prompt Engineering for Content Creation (ID: 541047ab-4271-4079-9e47-99906475d094)
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Prompt Engineering for Content Creation</h2><h3>Creating High-Quality Content with AI</h3><p>Content creation is one of the most popular applications of prompt engineering. This lesson teaches you how to use AI effectively for creating blog posts, articles, social media content, and more.</p><h3>Content Creation Workflow</h3><p>Effective content creation process: Research and planning, outline generation, draft creation, editing and refinement, SEO optimization, final polish. AI can assist at every stage. Systematic approach produces better results.</p><h3>Research and Planning</h3><p>Start with solid research. Use AI to: Gather background information, identify key topics and angles, analyze audience needs, research keywords, find relevant sources. Prompt: Research topic X for audience Y. Identify key themes, questions, and information needs. Provide sources.</p><h3>Outline Generation</h3><p>Create structured outlines. Prompt for: Main sections and subsections, logical flow, key points to cover, estimated length per section. Example prompt: Create a detailed outline for a 1500-word blog post about X for audience Y. Include introduction, 3-4 main sections, and conclusion. Specify key points for each section.</p><h3>Draft Creation</h3><p>Generate initial drafts. Effective draft prompts include: Topic and angle, target audience, desired tone and style, length requirements, key points to cover, format preferences. Example: Write the introduction section (200 words) for our blog post about X. Target audience is Y. Tone should be professional but approachable. Hook readers with a compelling statistic.</p><h3>Section-by-Section Approach</h3><p>Create content in sections. Benefits: Better quality per section, easier to review and refine, more control over flow, can adjust based on previous sections. Generate introduction, then each main section, then conclusion. Review and refine each before moving forward.</p><h3>Tone and Voice Control</h3><p>Maintain consistent voice. Define: Formality level (casual, professional, academic), perspective (first person, third person), personality (friendly, authoritative, playful), vocabulary (simple, technical, industry-specific). Include in every prompt for consistency.</p><h3>SEO Optimization</h3><p>Optimize for search engines. Prompt AI to: Include target keywords naturally, create compelling meta descriptions, suggest heading structure, optimize for readability, include internal linking opportunities. Example: Optimize this content for keyword X. Include keyword in headings and naturally throughout. Suggest meta description.</p><h3>Editing and Refinement</h3><p>Improve drafts systematically. Editing prompts: Check for clarity and flow, improve sentence structure, eliminate redundancy, enhance readability, verify accuracy. Example: Review this content and suggest improvements for clarity, flow, and engagement. Identify any redundant or unclear sections.</p><h3>Different Content Types</h3><p>Adapt approach for different formats. Blog posts: Informative, SEO-optimized, structured. Social media: Concise, engaging, platform-specific. Email newsletters: Personal, valuable, action-oriented. White papers: Authoritative, detailed, research-backed. Case studies: Story-driven, results-focused, credible. Each type needs different prompting strategy.</p><h3>Social Media Content</h3><p>Create platform-specific content. Twitter/X: Concise (280 chars), punchy, hashtags. LinkedIn: Professional, value-driven, longer form. Instagram: Visual-first, casual, emoji-friendly. Facebook: Conversational, community-focused. Prompt for platform-specific characteristics.</p><h3>Long-Form Content</h3><p>Handle longer pieces effectively. Strategy: Break into sections, maintain consistency across sections, track key themes, ensure logical flow, periodic summaries. Use context layering and prompt chaining for long content.</p><h3>Maintaining Consistency</h3><p>Keep voice and quality consistent. Techniques: Use same base prompt for all sections, reference previous sections, maintain style guide, periodic consistency checks. Example: Continue writing in the same tone and style as the previous sections. Maintain consistency in terminology and voice.</p><h3>Fact-Checking and Accuracy</h3><p>Verify AI-generated content. Always: Check facts and statistics, verify claims, validate sources, review for accuracy, add disclaimers if needed. AI can hallucinate - human verification essential.</p><h3>Avoiding Plagiarism</h3><p>Ensure originality. Strategies: Request original content, check for copied phrases, paraphrase and rewrite, add unique insights, cite sources properly. Use plagiarism checkers. Originality is critical.</p><h3>Brand Voice Integration</h3><p>Match company brand voice. Include in prompts: Brand personality traits, preferred terminology, tone guidelines, things to avoid, example content. Example: Write in our brand voice: friendly, helpful, never salesy. Use we not I. Avoid jargon. See examples: [examples].</p><h3>Content Templates</h3><p>Create reusable templates. Template components: Role and expertise, audience definition, content type and format, tone and style, key requirements, quality criteria. Fill in specifics for each piece. Saves time and ensures consistency.</p><h3>Quality Assurance</h3><p>Ensure high quality output. Check: Accuracy and factual correctness, clarity and readability, grammar and spelling, tone and voice consistency, SEO optimization, brand alignment. Multi-stage review process.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Content creation workflow: research, outline, draft, edit, optimize, polish</li><li>Create content section by section for better quality</li><li>Define and maintain consistent tone and voice</li><li>Optimize for SEO with keywords and structure</li><li>Adapt approach for different content types and platforms</li><li>Always fact-check and verify AI-generated content</li><li>Ensure originality and avoid plagiarism</li><li>Create reusable templates for efficiency</li></ul><p>In the next lesson, we will explore Prompt Engineering for Code Generation.</p></div>'
WHERE id = '541047ab-4271-4079-9e47-99906475d094';

-- LESSON 2: Prompt Engineering for Code Generation (ID: 059f53ab-1f9e-4c99-87a5-0499dc8957ed)
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Prompt Engineering for Code Generation</h2><h3>Using AI for Software Development</h3><p>AI code generation is transforming software development. This lesson teaches you how to use prompt engineering effectively for writing, reviewing, and debugging code.</p><h3>Code Generation Workflow</h3><p>Effective code generation process: Requirements specification, design and architecture, implementation, testing, review and refinement, documentation. AI assists throughout. Systematic approach produces better code.</p><h3>Specifying Requirements</h3><p>Clear requirements produce better code. Include: What the code should do, inputs and outputs, constraints and requirements, edge cases to handle, performance needs, language and framework. Example: Write a Python function that takes a list of integers and returns the median. Handle empty lists and even-length lists. Optimize for performance.</p><h3>Code Generation Prompts</h3><p>Effective code prompts include: Programming language and version, specific task or function, input and output specifications, constraints and requirements, coding standards to follow, error handling needs. Be specific and detailed.</p><h3>Incremental Development</h3><p>Build code incrementally. Start with: Basic structure and skeleton, core functionality, error handling, edge cases, optimization, documentation. Generate and test each piece before adding more. Easier to debug and refine.</p><h3>Code Review and Refinement</h3><p>Improve generated code. Review prompts: Check for bugs and errors, improve efficiency, enhance readability, add error handling, follow best practices. Example: Review this code for potential bugs, performance issues, and readability. Suggest improvements.</p><h3>Testing and Validation</h3><p>Generate tests for code. Test generation prompts: Create unit tests for this function, include edge cases, test error handling, aim for high coverage. Example: Write pytest unit tests for this function. Include tests for normal cases, edge cases, and error conditions.</p><h3>Debugging Assistance</h3><p>Use AI to debug code. Debugging prompts: Explain what this code does, identify potential bugs, suggest fixes for this error, explain why this is not working. Example: This code produces error X. Analyze the code and suggest fixes.</p><h3>Code Documentation</h3><p>Generate documentation. Documentation prompts: Write docstrings for this function, create README for this project, explain this code in plain language, document API endpoints. Example: Write comprehensive docstrings for this Python class including parameter descriptions and return values.</p><h3>Code Refactoring</h3><p>Improve existing code. Refactoring prompts: Refactor for better readability, improve performance, follow design patterns, reduce complexity, enhance maintainability. Example: Refactor this code to follow SOLID principles and improve readability.</p><h3>Different Programming Languages</h3><p>Adapt prompts for languages. Python: Pythonic idioms, PEP 8 style. JavaScript: Modern ES6+, async/await. Java: Object-oriented, design patterns. SQL: Query optimization, indexing. Specify language-specific requirements.</p><h3>Framework-Specific Code</h3><p>Generate framework code. React: Components, hooks, state management. Django: Models, views, templates. Express: Routes, middleware, error handling. Specify framework and version. Include framework conventions.</p><h3>Algorithm Implementation</h3><p>Implement algorithms effectively. Algorithm prompts: Specify algorithm clearly, define time/space complexity requirements, include example inputs and outputs, mention edge cases. Example: Implement binary search in Python. Time complexity O(log n). Handle empty arrays and duplicates.</p><h3>Code Translation</h3><p>Convert between languages. Translation prompts: Translate this Python code to JavaScript, maintain functionality, follow target language conventions, preserve comments. Verify translated code works correctly.</p><h3>Security Considerations</h3><p>Ensure code security. Security prompts: Check for SQL injection vulnerabilities, validate input sanitization, review authentication logic, identify security issues. Example: Review this code for security vulnerabilities including SQL injection, XSS, and authentication issues.</p><h3>Performance Optimization</h3><p>Optimize code performance. Optimization prompts: Improve time complexity, reduce memory usage, optimize database queries, parallelize where possible. Example: Optimize this code for performance. Current time complexity is O(n squared). Improve to O(n log n) or better.</p><h3>Code Quality Standards</h3><p>Maintain quality standards. Include in prompts: Coding style guides (PEP 8, Airbnb), naming conventions, comment requirements, complexity limits, test coverage. Example: Write code following PEP 8 style guide. Use descriptive variable names. Add comments for complex logic.</p><h3>Common Code Generation Mistakes</h3><p>Avoid common pitfalls. Mistake 1: Vague requirements (unclear what code should do). Solution: Specify requirements precisely. Mistake 2: No error handling (code breaks on edge cases). Solution: Explicitly request error handling. Mistake 3: Not testing generated code (bugs in production). Solution: Always test before using. Mistake 4: Blindly trusting AI (code may be incorrect). Solution: Review and understand all generated code.</p><h3>Best Practices</h3><p>Follow best practices for code generation. Always: Specify requirements clearly, review generated code, test thoroughly, understand the code, add comments and documentation, follow coding standards, consider security, optimize for maintainability. AI assists but human oversight is essential.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Code generation workflow: requirements, design, implementation, testing, review, documentation</li><li>Specify requirements clearly including language, task, inputs, outputs, constraints</li><li>Build incrementally and test each piece</li><li>Use AI for code review, testing, debugging, documentation</li><li>Adapt prompts for different languages and frameworks</li><li>Always review for security vulnerabilities</li><li>Test generated code thoroughly before using</li><li>Never blindly trust AI-generated code</li></ul><p>In the next lesson, we will explore Prompt Engineering for Data Analysis.</p></div>'
WHERE id = '059f53ab-1f9e-4c99-87a5-0499dc8957ed';

-- LESSON 3: Prompt Engineering for Data Analysis (ID: 9caa0061-6296-430d-8907-7868f160e683)
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Prompt Engineering for Data Analysis</h2><h3>Analyzing Data with AI</h3><p>AI can assist with data analysis from exploration to visualization to insights. This lesson teaches you how to use prompt engineering for effective data analysis.</p><h3>Data Analysis Workflow</h3><p>Systematic data analysis process: Data understanding and exploration, data cleaning and preparation, exploratory data analysis, statistical analysis, visualization, insights and recommendations. AI assists at every stage.</p><h3>Data Understanding</h3><p>Start by understanding your data. Use AI to: Summarize dataset characteristics, identify data types and formats, detect missing values, find outliers and anomalies, understand distributions. Example prompt: Analyze this dataset. Describe the columns, data types, missing values, and basic statistics. Identify any anomalies.</p><h3>Data Cleaning</h3><p>Prepare data for analysis. Cleaning tasks: Handle missing values, remove duplicates, fix data types, standardize formats, handle outliers. Example prompt: This dataset has missing values in columns X and Y. Suggest appropriate strategies for handling them based on the data characteristics.</p><h3>Exploratory Data Analysis</h3><p>Explore data patterns. EDA prompts: Identify correlations, find trends and patterns, detect outliers, understand distributions, segment data. Example: Perform exploratory analysis on this sales data. Identify trends over time, correlations between variables, and interesting patterns.</p><h3>Statistical Analysis</h3><p>Perform statistical tests. Analysis prompts: Calculate summary statistics, perform hypothesis tests, compute confidence intervals, analyze variance, test assumptions. Example: Test whether there is a significant difference in sales between regions A and B. Perform appropriate statistical test and interpret results.</p><h3>Data Visualization</h3><p>Create effective visualizations. Visualization prompts: Suggest appropriate chart types, create visualization code, design dashboard layouts, choose color schemes. Example: Create a Python matplotlib visualization showing sales trends by region over time. Use appropriate chart type and clear labels.</p><h3>Pattern Recognition</h3><p>Identify patterns in data. Pattern prompts: Find seasonal patterns, detect anomalies, identify clusters, discover associations. Example: Analyze this time series data for seasonal patterns, trends, and anomalies. Describe what you find.</p><h3>Predictive Analysis</h3><p>Make predictions from data. Predictive prompts: Forecast future values, identify predictive features, suggest modeling approaches, interpret predictions. Example: Based on historical sales data, forecast sales for next quarter. Explain your methodology and confidence level.</p><h3>Insight Generation</h3><p>Extract actionable insights. Insight prompts: Summarize key findings, identify business implications, suggest actions, prioritize insights. Example: Based on this customer data analysis, what are the top 3 insights and recommended actions for improving retention?</p><h3>Report Generation</h3><p>Create analysis reports. Report prompts: Summarize methodology, present findings, visualize results, provide recommendations. Example: Create an executive summary of this analysis including key findings, visualizations, and actionable recommendations. Target audience is non-technical executives.</p><h3>SQL Query Generation</h3><p>Generate database queries. SQL prompts: Specify data needed, define filters and joins, request aggregations, optimize queries. Example: Write a SQL query to find the top 10 customers by total purchase amount in the last year. Include customer name and total amount.</p><h3>Data Interpretation</h3><p>Interpret analysis results. Interpretation prompts: Explain what results mean, identify implications, suggest next steps, acknowledge limitations. Example: Interpret these regression results. What do the coefficients mean? Is the model significant? What are the limitations?</p><h3>Comparative Analysis</h3><p>Compare datasets or segments. Comparison prompts: Compare groups, identify differences, test significance, explain variations. Example: Compare customer behavior between segments A and B. Identify key differences and test if they are statistically significant.</p><h3>Trend Analysis</h3><p>Analyze trends over time. Trend prompts: Identify trends, detect changes, forecast future, explain drivers. Example: Analyze website traffic trends over the past year. Identify any significant changes and suggest possible explanations.</p><h3>Anomaly Detection</h3><p>Find unusual patterns. Anomaly prompts: Detect outliers, identify unusual patterns, investigate causes, assess impact. Example: Identify anomalies in this transaction data. For each anomaly, suggest possible explanations and whether it requires investigation.</p><h3>Data Quality Assessment</h3><p>Evaluate data quality. Quality prompts: Check completeness, assess accuracy, verify consistency, identify issues. Example: Assess the quality of this dataset. Identify any completeness, accuracy, or consistency issues that could affect analysis.</p><h3>Best Practices</h3><p>Follow data analysis best practices. Always: Understand data before analyzing, clean and prepare data properly, use appropriate statistical methods, visualize effectively, validate findings, acknowledge limitations, provide context for insights. AI assists but human judgment is critical.</p><h3>Common Mistakes</h3><p>Avoid analysis pitfalls. Mistake 1: Analyzing without understanding data. Solution: Always explore data first. Mistake 2: Ignoring data quality issues. Solution: Clean data before analysis. Mistake 3: Misinterpreting results. Solution: Understand statistical concepts. Mistake 4: Trusting AI blindly. Solution: Verify all findings.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Data analysis workflow: understand, clean, explore, analyze, visualize, insights</li><li>Use AI for data exploration, cleaning, statistical analysis, visualization</li><li>Generate SQL queries and analysis code with clear prompts</li><li>Extract actionable insights and create reports</li><li>Always validate AI findings and interpretations</li><li>Understand statistical concepts to interpret results correctly</li><li>Assess data quality before analyzing</li><li>Human judgment is critical for meaningful analysis</li></ul><p>Congratulations! You have completed Module 5. You now understand real-world applications of prompt engineering. In Module 6, we will conclude the course.</p></div>'
WHERE id = '9caa0061-6296-430d-8907-7868f160e683';

